

The following tutorials provide a progressive introduction to GetDP.
Each tutorial builds on the previous ones, introducing new modeling
concepts, formulation techniques and solver features. They are designed
to be studied in order.

@enumerate 
@item
@strong{Electrostatics}: Scalar potential formulation, Lagrange
elements, Dirichlet boundary conditions.
@item
@strong{Thermal}: Heat equation with conduction and convection, Neumann
and Robin boundary conditions, steady-state and transient analyses,
periodic constraints.
@item
@strong{Magnetostatics}: Vector potential formulation, infinite
elements, nonlinear materials with Newton-Raphson and Picard iterations.
@item
@strong{Magneto-quasistatics}: Eddy currents, frequency- and time-domain
analyses, axisymmetric models.
@item
@strong{Full wave}: Edge elements, absorbing boundary conditions,
Dirichlet constraint through an auxiliary resolution.
@item
@strong{Global quantities}: Global basis functions, floating potentials,
electrode charges and capacitances.
@item
@strong{Coupled problems}: a-v formulation with global currents and
voltages, magneto-thermal coupling, staggered resolution.
@item
@strong{Circuit coupling}: Lumped circuit elements, network constraints,
Kirchhoff's laws, tree-cotree gauging in 3D.
@item
@strong{Template library}: Generic formulation library, transformer with
magnetically coupled circuits, stranded coils, ferromagnetic
laminations.
@item
@strong{Gauging}: Tree-cotree vs.@ Coulomb gauge, 3D transformer model
with global coil basis functions.
@end enumerate

Each tutorial directory contains a @code{.geo} file (geometry and mesh),
a @code{.pro} file (finite element model) and a @code{README.md} with
instructions. The @code{.pro} and @code{.geo} files are heavily
commented -- the comments are the tutorial.

All tutorials can be run interactively with Gmsh (open the @code{.pro}
file, then press ``Run'') or from the command line (see the
@code{README.md} in each directory).


@unnumberedsec Further reading
The tutorials cover a fair amount of the underlying mathematics of the
finite element method and of the physics of the problems they address,
but they do not aim to be a self-contained treatise on either. The
following references are useful companions, grouped from most directly
relevant to the tutorials' main topic to more general background.

@itemize
@item
@strong{J.-M. Jin}, @emph{The Finite Element Method in
Electromagnetics}, 3rd edition, Wiley-IEEE Press, 2014 (ISBN
978-1-118-57136-1). Practitioner-oriented survey of the whole field;
mirrors the tutorial progression.

@item
@strong{G. Meunier (ed.)}, @emph{The Finite Element Method for
Electromagnetic Modeling}, Wiley-ISTE, 2008 (ISBN 978-1-84821-030-1).
Low-frequency applications, circuit coupling, motion, magneto-thermal
coupling; relevant to tutorials 1, 3, 4, 7, 8 and 9.

@item
@strong{A. Bossavit}, @emph{Computational Electromagnetism: Variational
Formulations, Complementarity, Edge Elements}, Academic Press, 1998
(ISBN 0-12-118710-1). Geometric / differential-forms view of
electromagnetism; relevant to tutorials 3, 4, 5, 7 and 10.

@item
@strong{P. Monk}, @emph{Finite Element Methods for Maxwell's Equations},
Oxford University Press, 2003 (ISBN 0-19-850888-3). Mathematical
reference for H(curl) elements and absorbing boundary conditions;
relevant to tutorial 5.

@item
@strong{D. Boffi, F. Brezzi, M. Fortin}, @emph{Mixed Finite Element
Methods and Applications}, Springer Series in Computational Mathematics
vol.@ 44, Springer, 2013 (ISBN 978-3-642-36518-8;
@uref{https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-36519-5,doi101007/978-3-642-36519-5}).
Theory of mixed methods and the de Rham complex underlying tutorials 5,
6, 7 and 10.

@item
@strong{A. Ern, J.-L. Guermond}, @emph{Theory and Practice of Finite
Elements}, Applied Mathematical Sciences vol.@ 159, Springer, 2004 (ISBN
0-387-20574-8;
@uref{https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4757-4355-5,doi101007/978-1-4757-4355-5}).
General-purpose graduate FE textbook; useful companion for the
underlying FE machinery.

@end itemize
