@node Tutorial 8 Circuit coupling in 2D and 3D
@section Tutorial 8: Circuit coupling in 2D and 3D
Two conductors modeled with finite elements are connected in parallel and driven by a voltage source through a series resistance and inductance. The lumped circuit elements and the finite element conductors are coupled through a network constraint that enforces Kirchhoff's laws via a global equation. In 3D, the vector potential is discretized with Whitney edge elements and a tree-cotree gauge ensures uniqueness. Both frequency-domain and time-domain analyses are supported.

@center@image{images/08-Circuit_coupling,14cm,,Screenshot of tutorial 08-Circuit_coupling}
@center See @url{https://gitlab.onelab.info/getdp/tutorials/-/tree/main/08-Circuit_coupling,tutorials/08-Circuit_coupling}.


@subsection Features
@itemize
@item
Circuit coupling in 2D and 3D a-v magneto-quasistatics
@item
Lumped resistors, inductors and voltage sources
@item
Discretization of the 3D vector potential with tree-cotree gauging
@item
Gradient basis functions for the 3D electric scalar potential
@end itemize

See the comments in @code{circuit.pro} and @code{circuit.geo} for details.

@subsection Running the tutorial
On the command line (2D analysis):

@verbatim
> gmsh circuit.geo -2
> getdp circuit.pro -solve Mag -pos MapMag
@end verbatim

On the command line (3D analysis):

@verbatim
> gmsh circuit.geo -3 -setnumber dim 3
> getdp circuit.pro -solve Mag -pos MapMag -setnumber dim 3
@end verbatim

Interactively with Gmsh: open @code{circuit.pro} with ``File->Open'', then press ``Run''.
