@node Tutorial 10 Tree-cotree and Coulomb gauging
@section Tutorial 10: Tree-cotree and Coulomb gauging
We consider a 3D version of the single-phase transformer of tutorial 9. The primary winding is driven by a voltage source and the secondary winding feeds a selectable load (resistance, inductance or capacitance). In 3D, the curl-curl equation does not uniquely determine the magnetic vector potential ``a'': gradient fields must be removed by imposing a gauge condition. Two strategies are presented and can be selected at runtime: tree-cotree gauging as in tutorial 8 (which constrains the degrees of freedom on a spanning tree of the mesh) and Coulomb gauging (which enforces ``div a = 0'' weakly via a scalar Lagrange multiplier). Both produce the same magnetic flux density ``b = curl a''.

@center@image{images/10-Gauging,14cm,,Screenshot of tutorial 10-Gauging}
@center See @url{https://gitlab.onelab.info/getdp/tutorials/-/tree/main/10-Gauging,tutorials/10-Gauging}.


@subsection Features
@itemize
@item
3D magneto-quasistatic formulation with circuit coupling
@item
Tree-cotree gauging via EdgesOfTreeIn / StartingOn
@item
Coulomb gauging via a mixed formulation with Lagrange multiplier
@item
Source current density obtained from an electrokinetic problem pre-computed on each coil
@end itemize

See the comments in @code{transfo.pro} and @code{transfo.geo} for details.

@subsection Running the tutorial
On the command line:

@verbatim
> gmsh transfo.geo -3
> getdp transfo.pro -solve Mag -pos Map
@end verbatim

